1
00:00:00,719 --> 00:00:08,285
[SPEAKER_04]: 2-321 subcommittee on zoning planning and development meeting notice Wednesday, March 22nd, 2023 at 6pm meeting is now called to order.

2
00:00:08,365 --> 00:00:09,586
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3
00:00:09,606 --> 00:00:10,427
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Collins.

4
00:00:10,707 --> 00:00:11,048
[SPEAKER_06]: Present.

5
00:00:11,668 --> 00:00:12,209
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Knight.

6
00:00:12,509 --> 00:00:13,410
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Knight is absent.

7
00:00:14,891 --> 00:00:15,511
[SPEAKER_06]: Chairman Behrs.

8
00:00:15,651 --> 00:00:15,992
[SPEAKER_04]: Present.

9
00:00:16,032 --> 00:00:17,053
[SPEAKER_04]: Two present, one absent.

10
00:00:17,093 --> 00:00:18,193
[SPEAKER_04]: The meeting is called to order.

11
00:00:18,274 --> 00:00:28,522
[SPEAKER_04]: There will be a meeting of the Medford City Council subcommittee on zoning planning and development on Wednesday, March 22nd, 2023 at 6pm in the Medford City Council Chamber on the second floor of Medford City Hall and via Zoom.

12
00:00:29,062 --> 00:00:32,983
[SPEAKER_04]: The purpose of this meeting is to discuss the condo conversion ordinance paper 22-321.

13
00:00:33,424 --> 00:00:39,506
[SPEAKER_04]: The subcommittee has invited Building Commissioner Bill Forty, Director of Planning, Development and Sustainability, Alicia Hunt, to attend this meeting.

14
00:00:39,626 --> 00:00:44,628
[SPEAKER_04]: For further information, aids and accommodations, contact the city clerk at 781-393-2425.

15
00:00:45,648 --> 00:00:47,769
[SPEAKER_04]: Sincerely yours, Zach Baer, Subcommittee Chair.

16
00:00:48,509 --> 00:00:50,069
[SPEAKER_04]: So welcome everyone today.

17
00:00:50,089 --> 00:00:57,232
[SPEAKER_04]: We are talking about a proposal to enact a condominium conversion ordinance here in the city of Medford.

18
00:00:57,920 --> 00:01:04,445
[SPEAKER_04]: Before we start, I just want to say that when we reviewed the records, we saw that this was actually referred to the subcommittee on housing.

19
00:01:05,745 --> 00:01:16,113
[SPEAKER_04]: So, if we need to make any sort of adjustment and maybe put a resolution on the agenda or something we may have to do that but we felt like a most two of us are on both committees.

20
00:01:16,613 --> 00:01:18,995
[SPEAKER_04]: This may well be the better committee for it to be on.

21
00:01:20,583 --> 00:01:22,585
[SPEAKER_04]: And we can have the discussion today on the item.

22
00:01:23,005 --> 00:01:34,254
[SPEAKER_04]: And if the council wants to send it back to housing or whatever else, then that's the prerogative of the body, but we don't foresee making any final decisions today.

23
00:01:34,415 --> 00:01:36,396
[SPEAKER_04]: So we can still have that conversation.

24
00:01:37,497 --> 00:01:46,665
[SPEAKER_04]: So with that, I'm going to turn it over to the lead sponsor of the item, Councilor Collins.

25
00:01:48,557 --> 00:01:50,038
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Vice President Beers.

26
00:01:52,239 --> 00:02:03,945
[SPEAKER_01]: I wanted to begin by just doing a brief overview of condo conversion ordinances as I understand them for the purpose of context for people in this room and anybody tuning in from home.

27
00:02:05,766 --> 00:02:10,629
[SPEAKER_01]: So, you know, the what and why of why we're having this discussion here today.

28
00:02:12,450 --> 00:02:15,772
[SPEAKER_01]: So to start with, you know, condo conversions in general,

29
00:02:16,764 --> 00:02:17,585
[SPEAKER_01]: What are we talking about here?

30
00:02:17,625 --> 00:02:18,325
[SPEAKER_01]: Why do they happen?

31
00:02:19,425 --> 00:02:36,833
[SPEAKER_01]: What we're seeing is, I mean, what we've been seeing really since the 80s, and this is when Massachusetts at the state level started regulating the conversion of rental units into condominiums, seeing a shortage of rental units that was being exacerbated by converting these to condo forms of ownership.

32
00:02:37,453 --> 00:02:43,636
[SPEAKER_01]: The state actually framed this as a public emergency when it published its regulation of this in the,

33
00:02:44,736 --> 00:02:47,557
[SPEAKER_01]: chapter 527 in 1983.

34
00:02:48,077 --> 00:02:56,319
[SPEAKER_01]: But the phenomenon that we're dealing with here really hasn't changed, and I think it's been picking up steam actually in communities such as ours in recent years.

35
00:02:57,159 --> 00:03:01,260
[SPEAKER_01]: There is a profit motive to converting rental units to condo forms of ownership.

36
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:03,540
[SPEAKER_01]: It greatly increases their resale value.

37
00:03:04,221 --> 00:03:05,801
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a good way for owners and developers

38
00:03:06,221 --> 00:03:08,785
[SPEAKER_01]: to capitalize on the property value of their holdings.

39
00:03:10,287 --> 00:03:11,289
[SPEAKER_01]: So why regulate this?

40
00:03:12,731 --> 00:03:16,436
[SPEAKER_01]: Developers stand to benefit very greatly from turning rental units into condos.

41
00:03:18,078 --> 00:03:18,479
[SPEAKER_01]: Meanwhile,

42
00:03:18,895 --> 00:03:23,717
[SPEAKER_01]: communities in our region, like I said, continue to have this drastic under supply of rental units.

43
00:03:24,738 --> 00:03:30,260
[SPEAKER_01]: This can contribute to the forces of gentrification, which we're already seeing in our community and many others around us.

44
00:03:31,021 --> 00:03:34,823
[SPEAKER_01]: It contributes to economic segregation as not everybody can afford to own their own home.

45
00:03:35,363 --> 00:03:46,048
[SPEAKER_01]: And so contributing or converting more rental units into owner occupier forms of property, speculative properties is harmful to our

46
00:03:47,152 --> 00:03:49,414
[SPEAKER_01]: harmful to the plurality and diversity of our community.

47
00:03:49,794 --> 00:03:56,779
[SPEAKER_01]: So this is just a way for the community to derive benefits from condo conversions, because developers are deriving benefits from them.

48
00:03:57,240 --> 00:04:11,311
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a way to infuse tenants stability measures into these conversions when they do happen through requirements like relocation payments, housing search assistance for the tenants that are displaced, and through other measures like payments into municipal affordable housing funds.

49
00:04:12,952 --> 00:04:16,173
[SPEAKER_01]: Like I mentioned, we're really not inventing the wheel here.

50
00:04:16,233 --> 00:04:27,075
[SPEAKER_01]: There are a lot of other communities in the greater Boston region that have local condo conversion ordinances that are either more specific or more strict than the floor that the state law provides.

51
00:04:28,275 --> 00:04:38,637
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a whole laundry list I provided for tonight, just five that we could look at in more detail that I think kind of create a sampling of directions that local communities similar to ours in certain ways have gone with.

52
00:04:39,177 --> 00:04:45,324
[SPEAKER_01]: They include Somerville, Boston, New Bedford, Marlboro, and Lexington.

53
00:04:45,905 --> 00:04:46,365
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Bill.

54
00:04:48,928 --> 00:05:00,381
[SPEAKER_01]: One other thing that I want to mention before we start getting into the weeds is that these ordinances are tailored to target for-profit developers or flippers, colloquially, not people who are

55
00:05:01,803 --> 00:05:19,596
[SPEAKER_01]: converting with the intent to transfer their properties to a relative and there are specific safeguards worked into all of the example ordinances that I researched to make sure that this is not something that's going to create an undue hardship for somebody who wants to turn their rental into a condo for a relative to live in or for themselves to occupy.

56
00:05:20,016 --> 00:05:28,923
[SPEAKER_01]: Really, it's targeting the people who are driving profit, the people or rather the commercial entities that are deriving profit from the value of our community.

57
00:05:31,583 --> 00:05:44,612
[SPEAKER_01]: So I want to just pause there after that kind of lengthy introduction for any preliminary questions or comments from my fellow subcommittee member or others in the room.

58
00:05:46,253 --> 00:05:47,394
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, no, I'm all good.

59
00:05:47,434 --> 00:05:49,095
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm happy to continue.

60
00:05:51,476 --> 00:06:00,022
[SPEAKER_04]: Either, you know, look through some of these or look through a tentative sample or hear from the planning director, building commissioner, wherever you want to go with it.

61
00:06:01,598 --> 00:06:02,098
[SPEAKER_01]: Great, thank you.

62
00:06:03,500 --> 00:06:16,870
[SPEAKER_01]: Unless there's other folks want to jump in right now, I'm happy to just kind of proceed with going through, walking us through the typical structure of condo conversion ordinances, touching a little bit on the state statute, and then maybe we can get into the weeds a little bit and comparing some of these other local examples.

63
00:06:19,933 --> 00:06:20,894
[SPEAKER_04]: Trying to share my screen.

64
00:06:31,135 --> 00:06:32,517
[SPEAKER_04]: You can go ahead while I work on it.

65
00:06:32,537 --> 00:06:32,917
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, great.

66
00:06:33,978 --> 00:06:40,125
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think I'll start with just a really quick rundown kind of going broad specifics.

67
00:06:40,165 --> 00:06:44,429
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll start with what the state says about condo conversions.

68
00:06:46,211 --> 00:06:51,257
[SPEAKER_01]: So like I said, there's this state statute that was enacted 40 years ago.

69
00:06:53,758 --> 00:06:57,241
[SPEAKER_01]: that does the same thing as the local ordinances also do.

70
00:06:57,321 --> 00:07:03,967
[SPEAKER_01]: It regulates how condo conversions happen and it requires certain conditions when they do happen.

71
00:07:03,987 --> 00:07:11,454
[SPEAKER_01]: The main tenants are, and I'm below this section right now.

72
00:07:11,594 --> 00:07:11,974
[SPEAKER_01]: No, you're good.

73
00:07:14,251 --> 00:07:14,711
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, you know what?

74
00:07:15,291 --> 00:07:17,592
[SPEAKER_01]: Sorry, I'm reading from the document that I didn't share with you.

75
00:07:19,052 --> 00:07:23,113
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'll just gloss through this really quickly, and then we'll bring it back to the local ordinances.

76
00:07:23,634 --> 00:07:35,097
[SPEAKER_01]: So the state statute sets up requirements for notice to tenants when an owner has an intent to convert their property into a condo.

77
00:07:38,038 --> 00:07:44,619
[SPEAKER_01]: The required notice is one year for tenants, but two years, and this is notice, two years of notice.

78
00:07:46,480 --> 00:07:47,440
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm sorry, let me start again.

79
00:07:48,460 --> 00:07:54,341
[SPEAKER_01]: So for the state statute and for all the local ordinances that we're going to look at, tenants are grouped into two categories.

80
00:07:54,821 --> 00:07:56,322
[SPEAKER_01]: One is protected tenants.

81
00:07:56,342 --> 00:08:02,863
[SPEAKER_01]: And in all the examples we're gonna look at, that means tenants that are elderly, disabled, or low or moderate income.

82
00:08:03,543 --> 00:08:06,964
[SPEAKER_01]: And so the state statute, the conditions are formulated the same way.

83
00:08:08,369 --> 00:08:27,385
[SPEAKER_01]: Owners with an intent to convert must give tenants in that protected class, two years notice before they have to vacate with an additional two years if they can't find comparable rental housing in the same city for all other tenants that aren't elderly disabled or lower moderate income, they have one year to vacate.

84
00:08:28,105 --> 00:08:30,708
[SPEAKER_01]: Just some other quick facts on the state statute.

85
00:08:30,748 --> 00:08:35,473
[SPEAKER_01]: Buildings with less than four units are exempt, so it's only buildings with four units or more.

86
00:08:35,513 --> 00:08:36,534
[SPEAKER_01]: It wouldn't be a triplex.

87
00:08:38,416 --> 00:08:45,102
[SPEAKER_01]: The state sets up a limit on rent increases during the notice period, so this is the period in between when the tenant learns

88
00:08:45,683 --> 00:09:01,192
[SPEAKER_01]: that their rental is being converted into a condo and when they have to vacate during that period, they'll remain a tenant and the landlord is not allowed to raise their rents for that time by more than either the consumer price index or by 10%, whichever is greater.

89
00:09:01,212 --> 00:09:10,637
[SPEAKER_01]: This is a measure to try to avoid or try to make it so landlords can't use a pretext for evicting a tenant earlier than the expiration of the notice period.

90
00:09:12,098 --> 00:09:15,161
[SPEAKER_01]: Just some others, and these will show up in the local ordinances as well.

91
00:09:15,601 --> 00:09:27,952
[SPEAKER_01]: Tenants are afforded the first right of refusal, also known as the right to purchase, on either the same or more favorable terms as those which will be extended to the general public when the condo is put up for sale.

92
00:09:29,413 --> 00:09:33,037
[SPEAKER_01]: Another stability measure in the state statute is relocation payments

93
00:09:34,597 --> 00:09:40,339
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a payment of $1,000 to tenants in that protected class and a payment of $750 to all other tenants.

94
00:09:40,799 --> 00:09:47,900
[SPEAKER_01]: So essentially that's saying you're being displaced by this conversion to compensate you, the owner is required to pay you this amount.

95
00:09:47,920 --> 00:09:51,421
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's a higher amount for those tenants in protected classes than it is for all other tenants.

96
00:09:54,622 --> 00:10:02,324
[SPEAKER_01]: And then the state also sets up penalties for violating this ordinance, which are by and large followed in all of the local ordinances that we're going to look at.

97
00:10:03,453 --> 00:10:09,156
[SPEAKER_01]: So that was all the regulatory floor set out on the state level.

98
00:10:10,536 --> 00:10:20,781
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'll just quickly gloss over the typical structure, the typical outline of many of the local condo conversion ordinances in Massachusetts.

99
00:10:21,261 --> 00:10:27,244
[SPEAKER_01]: I think there's in the ballpark of 12 to 15 of cities that have these in general.

100
00:10:31,688 --> 00:10:35,088
[SPEAKER_01]: Vice President Behrs, if you don't mind heading back to that document, thank you.

101
00:10:46,259 --> 00:10:47,099
[SPEAKER_01]: Great, that's perfect.

102
00:10:47,439 --> 00:10:48,740
[SPEAKER_01]: Just so that we can all look at the same thing.

103
00:10:49,960 --> 00:11:01,643
[SPEAKER_01]: So this is, in looking at, like I said, about five examples from various communities in Eastern Massachusetts, they all tend to follow this typical structure.

104
00:11:01,723 --> 00:11:09,705
[SPEAKER_01]: And of course, some ordinances have some sections and not others, but in general, they all contain, you know, title or purpose.

105
00:11:10,665 --> 00:11:20,348
[SPEAKER_01]: definitions, these are the standard things we see in almost all city ordinances, and then all of the requirements to go forward with a condo conversion.

106
00:11:20,708 --> 00:11:25,910
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's those notice requirements and again that's the notice and the length of notice that you need to give to tenants that will be displaced.

107
00:11:27,125 --> 00:11:30,888
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe there's differential conditions for occupied units versus unoccupied units.

108
00:11:30,948 --> 00:11:34,330
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe if the unit doesn't have a tenant in it, that could expedite the process for the owner.

109
00:11:35,371 --> 00:11:38,033
[SPEAKER_01]: Conditions for protected tenants, if there's a difference there.

110
00:11:38,693 --> 00:11:43,777
[SPEAKER_01]: Conditions on renting units while a conversion is going on or during a notice period.

111
00:11:45,818 --> 00:11:52,283
[SPEAKER_01]: Dealing with evictions during a conversion, if owners can do that, and if so, when the process they have to go through.

112
00:11:53,330 --> 00:11:55,972
[SPEAKER_01]: Many of them touch on tenant first refusal.

113
00:11:56,492 --> 00:12:09,460
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of them touch on city right to purchase or the city's designee right to purchase, relocation payments and relocation assistance to tenants, extension or modification of the rental agreement during the notice period.

114
00:12:10,301 --> 00:12:15,964
[SPEAKER_01]: In some cities, the number of conversions that an owner can do in a building or per calendar year is limited.

115
00:12:18,667 --> 00:12:30,130
[SPEAKER_01]: There's also requirements on what renovations may take place during a notice period, or if renovations are taking place, what sort of the experience of the tenant during that process, and the tenant's right to vacate during the notice period.

116
00:12:31,131 --> 00:12:35,132
[SPEAKER_01]: Finally, or well, not quite finally, but it feels like it should be finally already.

117
00:12:36,973 --> 00:12:41,594
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of these ordinances establish a specific review board to oversee this process.

118
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:43,660
[SPEAKER_01]: Not all of them do.

119
00:12:43,740 --> 00:12:50,362
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of them delegate existing city departments to oversee condo conversions.

120
00:12:51,262 --> 00:12:54,503
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of them set forth a specific permitting process.

121
00:12:55,023 --> 00:13:01,545
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of them set forth waivers or conditions under which other requirements can be skipped.

122
00:13:01,945 --> 00:13:05,566
[SPEAKER_01]: And we'll touch on that when we look through the individual ordinances and compare them.

123
00:13:07,226 --> 00:13:09,287
[SPEAKER_01]: Applicability, I mean, an example of that would be

124
00:13:10,583 --> 00:13:13,405
[SPEAKER_01]: Under the state statute, it's not applicable to buildings under four units.

125
00:13:14,086 --> 00:13:15,927
[SPEAKER_01]: Effective date, severability, and penalties.

126
00:13:15,947 --> 00:13:19,490
[SPEAKER_01]: And again, these are all things that are common to ordinances on many topics.

127
00:13:19,950 --> 00:13:28,597
[SPEAKER_01]: So that is the basic kind of bone structure of most of the local condo conversion ordinances, including the five that we can compare for our discussion tonight.

128
00:13:32,921 --> 00:13:35,643
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll just pause there in case there's any comments or questions so far.

129
00:13:36,283 --> 00:13:36,503
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

130
00:13:37,749 --> 00:13:40,570
[SPEAKER_04]: Would the next thing be actually comparing these different categories.

131
00:13:42,030 --> 00:13:45,591
[SPEAKER_04]: Across there could be pause there and maybe just I think at this point here from.

132
00:13:45,611 --> 00:13:52,873
[SPEAKER_04]: Commissioner 40 director hunt just on general thoughts around a condo ordinance if that's a good if you either you have them or.

133
00:13:52,893 --> 00:14:00,954
[SPEAKER_04]: I just want to get us to in the weeds before.

134
00:14:00,974 --> 00:14:07,156
[SPEAKER_00]: sort of see the good and the bad, and I will tell you that this is not something we've really dug into one thing that I.

135
00:14:08,127 --> 00:14:15,153
[SPEAKER_00]: looked at was what is our housing production plan say on this and it's kind of it's basically silent on the topic of condo conversions.

136
00:14:15,614 --> 00:14:31,187
[SPEAKER_00]: There is a lot of data there if anybody wants to know about what are the prices sale prices of houses versus condos and what are the rentals on apartments, just to understand how that all compares some of the pros and cons I actually had the opportunity.

137
00:14:31,812 --> 00:14:38,515
[SPEAKER_00]: to talk to our interim assessor briefly before this and just sort of get a snapshot idea on it.

138
00:14:39,015 --> 00:14:57,342
[SPEAKER_00]: And she just did want to, she advised me to remember that when you do condo conversions, that is good for municipal budgets because that is new growth and that is usually those units are improved and there's improvements and the sales and now you're adding to your tax levy.

139
00:14:58,182 --> 00:15:00,303
[SPEAKER_00]: And when you restrict that, that's not happening.

140
00:15:01,665 --> 00:15:14,488
[SPEAKER_00]: but that does have to be balanced against the need for more affordable housing and the very strong understanding that we do not have both enough affordable housing in the city that is deed restricted affordable housing and we don't have enough housing.

141
00:15:14,788 --> 00:15:18,449
[SPEAKER_00]: It is just affordable by the people who live here in the city.

142
00:15:19,189 --> 00:15:23,790
[SPEAKER_00]: People are getting priced out, they're getting forced out and that is very true.

143
00:15:24,750 --> 00:15:31,252
[SPEAKER_00]: And then to remember there are options around putting deed restrictions and to allowing that and they're incentivizing that

144
00:15:31,717 --> 00:15:43,742
[SPEAKER_00]: that it might be for an individual who owns a two-family house and they want to retire, maybe there's an option for them to condoize and put a deed restriction on the unit they're going to continue to live on.

145
00:15:44,802 --> 00:15:46,823
[SPEAKER_00]: Those are just some ideas that could occur.

146
00:15:46,843 --> 00:15:55,306
[SPEAKER_00]: I just kind of wanted to think in those big picture way as you're kind of getting into the details.

147
00:15:56,422 --> 00:16:02,044
[SPEAKER_00]: I have with me, Lily is one of the graduate students working in my office, and she did some research.

148
00:16:02,064 --> 00:16:14,327
[SPEAKER_00]: She was familiar with the Somerville Condo Conversion Ordinance, and they did a report on the results, because they've had Condo Conversion Ordinance for quite a long time.

149
00:16:15,567 --> 00:16:25,030
[SPEAKER_00]: And I have not had a chance to read that report, but Lily has, if it's helpful at any point, because that's somebody looking back and saying, how did this work in a community?

150
00:16:25,585 --> 00:16:27,226
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that is helpful for us.

151
00:16:27,566 --> 00:16:31,189
[SPEAKER_00]: We are very much like Somerville was a short while ago.

152
00:16:31,949 --> 00:16:34,991
[SPEAKER_00]: And we don't want to see people being forced out.

153
00:16:35,451 --> 00:16:40,595
[SPEAKER_00]: We also don't want to take away from people their retirement incomes and how do we balance that?

154
00:16:40,615 --> 00:16:50,001
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think I heard that in some of what you were talking about when you target at the developers who are flipping the properties and making a bundle and leaving.

155
00:16:50,558 --> 00:16:59,102
[SPEAKER_00]: versus the homeowner who actually, I talked to a Medford resident who was trying to figure out, what do I do with the two family?

156
00:16:59,262 --> 00:17:06,445
[SPEAKER_00]: I want to sell it to my daughter so that she can start to have equity, but I want to keep living here.

157
00:17:06,545 --> 00:17:07,446
[SPEAKER_00]: How do I do that?

158
00:17:07,786 --> 00:17:11,588
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we do that or do I sell the whole building and the both of us move out of Medford?

159
00:17:13,208 --> 00:17:16,350
[SPEAKER_00]: Those are real conversations that people have in Medford.

160
00:17:16,690 --> 00:17:18,871
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just want to bring up that that is real.

161
00:17:19,368 --> 00:17:20,428
[SPEAKER_00]: and that is going on here.

162
00:17:21,249 --> 00:17:22,629
[SPEAKER_00]: So just food for thought.

163
00:17:22,989 --> 00:17:26,350
[SPEAKER_00]: We really haven't gotten into the weeds on this yet.

164
00:17:26,970 --> 00:17:28,831
[SPEAKER_00]: Although Lily has more than I do in the weeds.

165
00:17:29,291 --> 00:17:32,152
[SPEAKER_04]: Do we have, just before you sit down, Alicia, sorry.

166
00:17:32,192 --> 00:17:34,693
[SPEAKER_04]: Do we have any data on condo conversions in Medford?

167
00:17:35,533 --> 00:17:35,993
[SPEAKER_00]: I do not.

168
00:17:36,213 --> 00:17:36,473
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

169
00:17:38,394 --> 00:17:46,917
[SPEAKER_00]: It's conceivable to me that that might be something the assessor might have, but we've never asked for it.

170
00:17:51,371 --> 00:17:55,954
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, yeah, Building Commissioner.

171
00:17:57,354 --> 00:18:00,997
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi everyone.

172
00:18:01,017 --> 00:18:12,104
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I guess I would say maybe briefly that some of the research I did on Somerville's particularly kind of focused on outcomes so it seemed like they were deciding like what kind of outcomes they wanted and tailoring their ordinance to fit that.

173
00:18:12,625 --> 00:18:15,107
[SPEAKER_02]: And just a couple of highlights from their report.

174
00:18:16,367 --> 00:18:24,953
[SPEAKER_02]: They updated their condo conversion ordinance to include stronger tenant protections in 2019, and it went into effect for financial year 2020.

175
00:18:25,733 --> 00:18:30,496
[SPEAKER_02]: So they have a couple years of data from before and after, and there were a couple of broad trends.

176
00:18:30,616 --> 00:18:33,098
[SPEAKER_02]: They didn't have any permits that they denied.

177
00:18:33,438 --> 00:18:38,441
[SPEAKER_02]: Some of them were conditionally approved, sort of indicating that the owners were following through on these new obligations.

178
00:18:39,002 --> 00:18:45,665
[SPEAKER_02]: They also had a greater number of condo conversions by owner occupants, as opposed to developers.

179
00:18:46,665 --> 00:18:48,927
[SPEAKER_02]: So those were two kind of interesting data points there.

180
00:18:50,807 --> 00:18:51,488
[SPEAKER_03]: Great, thank you.

181
00:18:53,308 --> 00:18:54,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Mr Chairman.

182
00:18:54,649 --> 00:18:56,490
[SPEAKER_03]: So, I can.

183
00:18:57,288 --> 00:19:00,211
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't have a lot of working experience with this ordinance.

184
00:19:00,251 --> 00:19:04,094
[SPEAKER_03]: In fact, I've never had to enforce this in any city or town that I've worked in.

185
00:19:05,115 --> 00:19:14,743
[SPEAKER_03]: But I can give you just a little bit of an idea on construction trends and tendencies where buildings might be renovated.

186
00:19:15,343 --> 00:19:20,668
[SPEAKER_03]: It's been my experience as code enforcement that what I find is that when a person

187
00:19:21,543 --> 00:19:26,885
[SPEAKER_03]: can take a non-conforming four-family, knock it down, and build four units.

188
00:19:28,186 --> 00:19:31,407
[SPEAKER_03]: That's when you will find that those units will be sold separately.

189
00:19:31,527 --> 00:19:40,791
[SPEAKER_03]: I can tell you from a builder's standpoint that taking over a two or a three-family with floors one on top of the other and converting them into condos doesn't

190
00:19:41,131 --> 00:19:44,774
[SPEAKER_03]: It doesn't happen as often as you would think anyways.

191
00:19:45,634 --> 00:19:52,519
[SPEAKER_03]: A lot of times when a property has been substantially renovated, usually it's not for condominium purposes.

192
00:19:52,559 --> 00:19:59,985
[SPEAKER_03]: And I can tell you that in converting to condominiums, it creates all kinds of problems.

193
00:20:00,005 --> 00:20:02,746
[SPEAKER_03]: The first thing, obviously, is the fire separation between units.

194
00:20:02,766 --> 00:20:04,248
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a one hour fire separation.

195
00:20:04,808 --> 00:20:06,489
[SPEAKER_03]: Sound attenuation is a big deal.

196
00:20:06,969 --> 00:20:09,011
[SPEAKER_03]: It can become an encumbrance on a title.

197
00:20:09,674 --> 00:20:18,078
[SPEAKER_03]: If you have a condo that does not sound attenuated now it's in the state building code right now that you have to sound attenuation between units, whether that be horizontal or vertical.

198
00:20:19,239 --> 00:20:34,046
[SPEAKER_03]: I would just tell you that it's a hassle to divide up a property into title to separate title on an existing building that otherwise is not really stripped down to the bones and kind of rebuild you know to build a sound attenuated

199
00:20:35,327 --> 00:20:42,354
[SPEAKER_03]: assembly requires a double wall it's almost like a party wall and it would really, it has a tendency to be difficult.

200
00:20:43,095 --> 00:20:53,206
[SPEAKER_03]: So I would say that on your average, and this is just, you know what I'm gathering from what I see here Medford what I've seen in Waltham and, and certainly what I've seen in Newton is that when a person buys

201
00:20:53,957 --> 00:20:59,982
[SPEAKER_03]: a two or three family, it's likely that that property will will remain rental only because rents are very high.

202
00:21:01,223 --> 00:21:04,906
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't see, you know, as long as rent markets stay high.

203
00:21:05,927 --> 00:21:11,831
[SPEAKER_03]: It's almost more profitable for a builder to buy a property converted and get, you know,

204
00:21:13,332 --> 00:21:23,976
[SPEAKER_03]: $3,030 $500 a unit, you know, for something that's substantially got a lot of room, you know, number of bedrooms, all that stuff kind of plays into into, you know, the plan.

205
00:21:24,837 --> 00:21:28,958
[SPEAKER_03]: It's all financial, no matter what, you know, nobody buys a property, so they can make it look nice.

206
00:21:29,479 --> 00:21:30,779
[SPEAKER_03]: They buy a property to make profit.

207
00:21:30,919 --> 00:21:37,882
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, given the fact that, you know, we have Tufts University, we have the, you know, we have high speed transit,

208
00:21:38,502 --> 00:21:40,342
[SPEAKER_03]: all of those things kind of play a factor.

209
00:21:41,243 --> 00:21:57,126
[SPEAKER_03]: I saw a lot of condo conversion in Waltham, but it was only after a builder was able to not only take down an existing house, but build four units and, you know, each condo unit having, you know, 3000 plus square feet, you know, that's a pretty good size condo.

210
00:21:57,146 --> 00:21:59,006
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the size of a single family home.

211
00:21:59,046 --> 00:22:06,168
[SPEAKER_03]: And they were marketing out at over a million dollars, you know, those are the kinds of big conversions that I saw because the zoning ordinance was liberal.

212
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:21,445
[SPEAKER_03]: You know here, you're, you're kind of limited to the amount of space property that you have in an average single family residence, you know, multifamily residence district you know you're seven to 10,000 square feet.

213
00:22:22,086 --> 00:22:25,587
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't see a lot of this conversion going on right now.

214
00:22:26,517 --> 00:22:44,826
[SPEAKER_03]: Although there is no reporting requirement in my department at the time, it's very, what happens is if somebody wants to renovate a property, what we would have to do is divide it up into two separate building permits and issue two building permits, and then therefore two separate certificates of occupancy.

215
00:22:44,926 --> 00:22:50,889
[SPEAKER_03]: Obviously, if you're gonna divide a property, you would want your own certificate of occupancy for your own fitness of your own unit.

216
00:22:51,650 --> 00:22:53,991
[SPEAKER_03]: We have not seen hardly any of that.

217
00:22:54,631 --> 00:22:56,172
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't see it as being,

218
00:22:56,888 --> 00:22:58,469
[SPEAKER_03]: huge problem here in the city.

219
00:22:58,930 --> 00:23:02,193
[SPEAKER_03]: However, you know, notwithstanding any of that information.

220
00:23:03,274 --> 00:23:08,779
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that maybe maybe two family or less should probably be taken out of the equation.

221
00:23:08,979 --> 00:23:12,903
[SPEAKER_03]: Because if you do have a two family and a builder decides that they do want to convert it.

222
00:23:13,563 --> 00:23:20,988
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, you know, that's creating two single family homes and you know that that does help with the growth of the residential market.

223
00:23:21,528 --> 00:23:38,278
[SPEAKER_03]: I think when you get into, you know, like we have this big 40 be coming up 350 units, you know, that might be something that you want to restrict, you know, even buildings with 50 units 25 units 10 units, those, those foreseeably are, you know, could be something that I think

224
00:23:38,738 --> 00:23:44,342
[SPEAKER_03]: But I think that there should be a minimum threshold here of what qualifies and maybe even up to a three family.

225
00:23:44,382 --> 00:23:51,067
[SPEAKER_03]: The only reason I say that is because the one and two family dwelling code is its own standalone code in the state building code.

226
00:23:51,187 --> 00:24:01,155
[SPEAKER_03]: And I very rarely see two families being converted to condos, unless the building has been demolished and rebuilt.

227
00:24:01,295 --> 00:24:04,758
[SPEAKER_03]: So I just thought I would give you that insight anyways.

228
00:24:05,838 --> 00:24:06,579
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Commissioner.

