324
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:46,841
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, is it too small?

325
00:33:49,321 --> 00:33:51,682
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

326
00:33:52,102 --> 00:33:54,482
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

327
00:33:56,843 --> 00:33:57,243
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

328
00:33:57,283 --> 00:34:00,864
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'll say it out loud when we scroll down a page or something like that.

329
00:34:01,224 --> 00:34:01,504
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

330
00:34:01,544 --> 00:34:08,145
[SPEAKER_04]: And I asked just cause that's helpful feedback as we look at improvements to this chamber for having meetings like this and doing stuff like this.

331
00:34:10,686 --> 00:34:10,986
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

332
00:34:11,126 --> 00:34:11,366
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks.

333
00:34:13,300 --> 00:34:13,821
[SPEAKER_01]: Good to know.

334
00:34:14,421 --> 00:34:18,305
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, so we're on the page that's titled comparison five local examples.

335
00:34:18,385 --> 00:34:25,192
[SPEAKER_01]: So with this, I just threw together five of the again, I think it's like 12 to 15 municipalities and

336
00:34:25,881 --> 00:34:29,122
[SPEAKER_01]: in Massachusetts, it could be more that have a local condo conversion ordinance.

337
00:34:29,722 --> 00:34:44,787
[SPEAKER_01]: I was trying to pick a selection of communities that are neighboring Medford in the Metro North region, you know, have certain similar demographic similarities, but maybe aren't as proximate, and then others that I thought, you know, kind of

338
00:34:45,233 --> 00:34:52,096
[SPEAKER_01]: might mirror us in terms of municipal capacity, in terms of the scale and the ambitiousness of their ordinance.

339
00:34:53,217 --> 00:35:04,282
[SPEAKER_01]: So just going top to bottom, like I said, there's a common structure that all of these ordinances follow, and the title and purpose is not really important, except that I do think it's interesting that in several of

340
00:35:05,385 --> 00:35:05,765
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, sorry.

341
00:35:05,825 --> 00:35:12,512
[SPEAKER_01]: So the cities that we're going to be looking at specifically are Somerville, Boston, Marlboro, New Bedford, and Lexington, left to right.

342
00:35:12,872 --> 00:35:29,108
[SPEAKER_01]: And I do think it is interesting that like the state statute, most of these cities, except for Boston and Marlboro, specifically call out in their purpose sections at the top of the ordinance, a declaration of emergency or a statement of emergency.

343
00:35:29,892 --> 00:35:33,376
[SPEAKER_01]: regarding the scarcity of rentals in those communities.

344
00:35:33,396 --> 00:35:39,621
[SPEAKER_01]: So I just think that's an interesting bit of context to see how other communities are framing that in the actual language of their ordinance.

345
00:35:42,484 --> 00:35:54,976
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think one of the, most of the requirements prescribed under this ordinance target the experience of the tenant

346
00:35:55,562 --> 00:35:58,143
[SPEAKER_01]: that's living in a unit that is being converted into a condo.

347
00:35:58,323 --> 00:36:03,045
[SPEAKER_01]: So a lot of these requirements, that's the mechanism that's trying to affect or improve that tenant's experience.

348
00:36:03,585 --> 00:36:17,151
[SPEAKER_01]: Because if this were a completely unregulated system, and of course that's not the case because we have that state statute setting the floor, this could be a situation where a owner says, hey, by the way, you have to get out because this is going to be a condo soon.

349
00:36:18,452 --> 00:36:27,959
[SPEAKER_01]: So this first requirement, notice period, and if you can't hear me, just wave at me because the fan just came on in the chambers and I can't hear myself.

350
00:36:31,321 --> 00:36:42,850
[SPEAKER_01]: This seeks to say, this seeks to create a runway for tenants so that they have a longer amount of time to adjust to the fact that they have to move out because their rental is becoming a condo.

351
00:36:44,887 --> 00:36:51,858
[SPEAKER_01]: Here I'll skip down a couple rows because where do I have this so all of these ordinances.

352
00:36:54,587 --> 00:37:01,030
[SPEAKER_01]: identify protected tenants as tenants that are elderly, disabled, or low or moderate income.

353
00:37:01,570 --> 00:37:04,872
[SPEAKER_01]: So when I'm referring to protected tenants, it's tenants in those three categories.

354
00:37:05,312 --> 00:37:14,617
[SPEAKER_01]: So in Somerville, you can see protected tenants are given five years before they have to vacate after the owner notifies them that they have an intent to convert.

355
00:37:14,997 --> 00:37:16,818
[SPEAKER_01]: All other tenants are given just one year.

356
00:37:17,389 --> 00:37:28,696
[SPEAKER_01]: to vacate, all of the other cities follow a similar structure where protected tenants are given some amount of longer time than all other tenants, a longer runway.

357
00:37:30,397 --> 00:37:46,668
[SPEAKER_01]: Except for Lexington, where the notice period isn't specified, but a condition of the conversion license, which is promulgated by the board,

358
00:37:48,053 --> 00:37:52,696
[SPEAKER_01]: is part of the board's decision on whether or not that owner will be issued a conversion license in the first place.

359
00:37:59,120 --> 00:38:08,526
[SPEAKER_01]: I think I'm going to skip past a couple of these that seem a little bit less substantial, but renting units during a conversion, I think, is one that

360
00:38:10,277 --> 00:38:13,820
[SPEAKER_01]: think could be relevant in a community like ours, or at least useful to articulate.

361
00:38:15,121 --> 00:38:21,385
[SPEAKER_01]: Many of the ordinances are silent on this, but Somerville and Boston specify that.

362
00:38:22,986 --> 00:38:30,772
[SPEAKER_01]: So if you have a unit where there's an intent to convert and the previous tenant moves out, so now the unit is vacant, perhaps the owner

363
00:38:32,101 --> 00:38:38,244
[SPEAKER_01]: wants to have a tenant to fill that void because they're still perhaps going through the conversion permitting process perhaps they're still planning the renovation.

364
00:38:39,465 --> 00:38:47,589
[SPEAKER_01]: They can rent it out to a new tenant, while the conversion permit processes and is ongoing, while they're working through that process.

365
00:38:51,831 --> 00:39:05,551
[SPEAKER_01]: Those prospective those new tenants won't be entitled to the protections of this ordinance like they won't get the five year notice period if there's a relocation payment if there's relocation assistance, they're not automatically entitled to that if they move in when it's already known that the conversion is going on.

366
00:39:07,073 --> 00:39:22,574
[SPEAKER_01]: They are informed that the conversion is already gone is going on, if the owner fails to or neglects to inform them that their rental unit will become a condo, then they will become protected and entitled to any of the other benefits such as relocation payment or an extended notice period.

367
00:39:25,062 --> 00:39:38,753
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that's one that we might want to consider, it might not be necessary, but I think it's another window into a lever that some of these ordinances include for making sure that tenants are really considered and protected during this process.

368
00:39:39,994 --> 00:39:43,877
[SPEAKER_01]: Eviction during conversion, this is kind of the main thrust of the ordinance.

369
00:39:44,317 --> 00:39:46,319
[SPEAKER_01]: This is present in the state statute as well.

370
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:57,325
[SPEAKER_01]: Essentially, the ordinance is seeking to make sure that tenants can't be evicted to make renovation or rehabilitation or conversion easier for the owner.

371
00:39:57,345 --> 00:40:04,028
[SPEAKER_01]: And there's also prohibitions on kind of inventing pretexts so that tenants can be evicted sooner.

372
00:40:04,508 --> 00:40:13,893
[SPEAKER_01]: So eviction is prohibited until that notice period expires, whether that's one year or five years or other, depending on the city.

373
00:40:16,155 --> 00:40:25,342
[SPEAKER_01]: And just for context, one exception here, and I'm on page number three, I immediately forgot to mention we were shifting pages.

374
00:40:26,222 --> 00:40:35,008
[SPEAKER_01]: In Lexington, the Condo Conversion Board issues licenses for an eviction.

375
00:40:35,049 --> 00:40:45,436
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's another way that that city regulates and modulates the protection of tenants from eviction by saying, if you want to evict a tenant, you actually have to get a license to do that.

376
00:40:48,522 --> 00:40:59,385
[SPEAKER_01]: So now we're getting on to tenant first right of refusal and city slash designee right to purchase, which, you know, speaking just for myself, are two areas that I'd like us to look really closely at.

377
00:41:02,546 --> 00:41:07,387
[SPEAKER_01]: In all of these cities, except for Lexington, tenants have some first right of refusal.

378
00:41:07,447 --> 00:41:10,348
[SPEAKER_01]: So that means if a condo conversion is going on

379
00:41:11,288 --> 00:41:19,593
[SPEAKER_01]: and it's going to be put up for sale as opposed to an owner converting it into a condo and then they're going to convey it to a relative or if they're going to occupy it themselves.

380
00:41:21,635 --> 00:41:26,598
[SPEAKER_01]: If it is going to be put up for sale, tenants have the first, they have the first bite at the apple.

381
00:41:28,239 --> 00:41:36,384
[SPEAKER_01]: They have the right to purchase their unit, the unit that they lived in on the same terms or more favorable terms that would be offered to the general public.

382
00:41:38,932 --> 00:41:43,213
[SPEAKER_01]: There's different sort of right to purchase periods for different cities.

383
00:41:43,273 --> 00:41:49,354
[SPEAKER_01]: Sometimes it's, you know, Somerville's is 120 days for most tenants and 180 days for protected tenants.

384
00:41:50,874 --> 00:41:52,415
[SPEAKER_01]: In Boston, it's 90 days.

385
00:41:54,795 --> 00:42:00,996
[SPEAKER_01]: But that is something that is actually also present in the state statute.

386
00:42:01,036 --> 00:42:04,497
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think Lexington doesn't get specific.

387
00:42:06,008 --> 00:42:11,973
[SPEAKER_01]: on tenant first right of refusal, so it would revert back to the floor provided by the state statute.

388
00:42:13,094 --> 00:42:23,463
[SPEAKER_01]: And then, interestingly, this is at the bottom of page three, some ordinances designate that the city has a right to purchase or the city's designee has a right to purchase

389
00:42:24,020 --> 00:42:27,263
[SPEAKER_01]: if the tenant does not want to exercise their right of first refusal.

390
00:42:28,223 --> 00:42:31,286
[SPEAKER_01]: Not every city does this, Boston doesn't do this, New Bedford doesn't do this.

391
00:42:31,926 --> 00:42:39,773
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think this is something that we might really want to look at, especially since it looks like we might very soon have an affordable housing trust.

392
00:42:40,313 --> 00:42:41,875
[SPEAKER_01]: Just a couple examples of how

393
00:42:43,353 --> 00:42:45,314
[SPEAKER_01]: This plays out in a couple other cities.

394
00:42:45,834 --> 00:42:52,737
[SPEAKER_01]: In Somerville, again, this is after a tenant has said, no, thank you, I don't wanna exercise my right of first refusal.

395
00:42:54,477 --> 00:43:02,181
[SPEAKER_01]: The city or its designee can purchase that unit and maintain it in perpetuity as affordable housing.

396
00:43:03,161 --> 00:43:08,343
[SPEAKER_01]: And again, there's an exception for if the newly converted condo is conveyed to a relative.

397
00:43:09,283 --> 00:43:10,464
[SPEAKER_01]: In Marlborough,

398
00:43:13,930 --> 00:43:22,754
[SPEAKER_01]: there isn't a specific city right to purchase, but there are conditions for some requirements of the ordinance being waived entirely.

399
00:43:22,835 --> 00:43:33,920
[SPEAKER_01]: And one condition for waiving ordinance requirements is set payments or bonding to their affordable housing fund or affordable housing trust.

400
00:43:34,020 --> 00:43:43,545
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's not a city right to purchase, but it's another way of enforcing that affordable housing and perpetuity, whether that's compensation or actual unit is being afforded to the city.

401
00:43:45,962 --> 00:44:02,925
[SPEAKER_01]: Similarly, in Lexington, the conversion license is conditioned on 10 to 20% of the units that are being converted being offered to the Housing Authority, the Housing Assistance Board, or any other entity, which could be a city-designated nonprofit, that will hold them as permanently affordable units.

402
00:44:03,945 --> 00:44:14,907
[SPEAKER_01]: So these are some different mechanisms, some different ways of making sure that the city has an opportunity to get some affordable housing out of

403
00:44:15,754 --> 00:44:16,614
[SPEAKER_01]: condo conversions.

404
00:44:20,436 --> 00:44:28,400
[SPEAKER_01]: So kind of going, moving on to page four here, and this is going back to the tenant stability, tenant experience side of things, relocation payments.

405
00:44:28,961 --> 00:44:31,782
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that these are kind of integral to the tenant experience.

406
00:44:32,752 --> 00:44:40,078
[SPEAKER_01]: of the ordinance and this is something that I would like for us to discuss further, and relocation assistance which goes hand in hand with that.

407
00:44:41,380 --> 00:44:55,732
[SPEAKER_01]: So these are compensation that owners must pay to tenants that are displaced by condo conversion to offset, you know, supposedly to offset the cost of moving since their rental is being converted into a condo that will be put up for sale.

408
00:44:56,540 --> 00:45:07,027
[SPEAKER_01]: And for all of these, these are all conditioned on, these would not apply if in any city where the tenant takes the owner up on their right to purchase.

409
00:45:07,428 --> 00:45:09,449
[SPEAKER_01]: So these are just for tenants that are moving out.

410
00:45:10,330 --> 00:45:11,390
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a pretty big range here.

411
00:45:11,470 --> 00:45:17,975
[SPEAKER_01]: So the state sets the floor at $1,000 in a relocation payment for protected tenants and $750 for all other tenants.

412
00:45:22,952 --> 00:45:24,493
[SPEAKER_01]: Some cities go a lot higher.

413
00:45:25,033 --> 00:45:30,197
[SPEAKER_01]: In Boston, it's $15,000 for protected tenants and $10,000 for all other tenants.

414
00:45:30,677 --> 00:45:35,941
[SPEAKER_01]: In Somerville, it's $10,000 for protected tenants and $6,000 for all other tenants.

415
00:45:36,161 --> 00:45:49,910
[SPEAKER_01]: And Somerville also has a stipulation that the dollar amount should be annually adjusted according to the Consumer Price Index, which I think is a great idea to include no matter what dollar amount we might decide on should we go forward with this idea.

416
00:45:51,310 --> 00:46:11,385
[SPEAKER_01]: In Lexington, I just want to note because this is a much more flexible way of doing this, the dollar amount for relocation payments to tenants isn't specified, but the conversion licenses given to owners are subject to conditions, which include some public conditions such as how bad is our housing shortage right now.

417
00:46:12,145 --> 00:46:20,774
[SPEAKER_01]: but also on the reasonable arrangements that the owners propose and agree to, to alleviate the hardship of tenants affected by the proposed conversion.

418
00:46:20,814 --> 00:46:29,843
[SPEAKER_01]: So that essentially sets the owner and the city and the tenant up for a discussion, if not a negotiation, as opposed to prescribing a specific dollar amount.

419
00:46:30,564 --> 00:46:31,485
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's another approach.

420
00:46:34,195 --> 00:46:44,068
[SPEAKER_01]: relocation assistance, so that's not monetary compensation, but that requires that the owner help tenants find comparable new housing within the same municipality.

421
00:46:44,528 --> 00:46:47,632
[SPEAKER_01]: For a lot of these cities it's for protected tenants only.

422
00:46:47,652 --> 00:46:51,157
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm actually scanning to see.

423
00:46:54,503 --> 00:46:59,567
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, in none of these examples does that extend to all tenants.

424
00:46:59,827 --> 00:47:02,049
[SPEAKER_01]: It's extended to only protected tenants.

425
00:47:02,809 --> 00:47:14,498
[SPEAKER_01]: And in Boston and Marlborough, it's explicitly stated that if appropriate new housing can't be found, then the notice period can be extended for up to two additional years.

426
00:47:14,738 --> 00:47:16,279
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's again, lengthening the runways.

427
00:47:16,319 --> 00:47:20,903
[SPEAKER_01]: Think if it's too hard, if we can't find you a new place to move into, then you can live here for another two years.

428
00:47:25,564 --> 00:47:31,666
[SPEAKER_01]: Really quickly, this is sort of a blanket one across all municipalities that we looked at, the extension of the rental agreement.

429
00:47:31,686 --> 00:47:51,233
[SPEAKER_01]: So this is saying during that notice period, during that runway, when tenants know that their rental is being converted into a condo and they're still living in that unit for the time being, this is again, a way to make sure that owners are not finding pretext to evict their tenants sooner by capping rent increases.

430
00:47:51,293 --> 00:47:52,533
[SPEAKER_01]: So in all of these examples,

431
00:47:53,768 --> 00:48:02,594
[SPEAKER_01]: During that notice period when the tenant is still living in the unit, rent cannot be increased by more than the consumer price index or 10%, whichever is less.

432
00:48:07,538 --> 00:48:09,239
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, just a few more to go over here.

433
00:48:09,299 --> 00:48:17,285
[SPEAKER_01]: At the bottom of this page, sum, so in this sample size,

434
00:48:19,373 --> 00:48:26,775
[SPEAKER_01]: Marlborough is the only city that sets a limit on the number of units that can be converted to condos in any building per calendar year.

435
00:48:26,795 --> 00:48:31,916
[SPEAKER_01]: It says no more than 25, no more than 25% of units can be converted in any given year.

436
00:48:32,076 --> 00:48:41,659
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know if that is something that would be super relevant to our community given the type of this construction that we've, that type of this renovation that we've been seeing so far.

437
00:48:42,399 --> 00:48:47,120
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it's something that's sort of interesting to consider when we look at, as we continue to dig into the data of

438
00:48:47,952 --> 00:48:51,134
[SPEAKER_01]: what units are being converted into condos and which aren't.

439
00:48:53,896 --> 00:49:14,730
[SPEAKER_01]: And similarly, another more flexible way to do this, again, comes from Lexington, where there isn't a cap specified, but the conversion licenses are conditioned on those questions of how bad is our rental shortage currently, and the conversion board can make a determination on whether to approve a conversion license or not based on the need for rental housing in the community.

440
00:49:20,458 --> 00:49:24,221
[SPEAKER_01]: I want to skip down here to the second half of page five.

441
00:49:24,642 --> 00:49:33,329
[SPEAKER_01]: I think this will be something interesting for us to consider, the establishment of a review board that kind of oversees this process.

442
00:49:33,369 --> 00:49:42,717
[SPEAKER_01]: And in different communities, the review board has more or less authority or an involvement with condo conversions and the experience of both owners and tenants during that process.

443
00:49:46,320 --> 00:49:48,542
[SPEAKER_01]: Most of, so Somerville,

444
00:49:50,310 --> 00:49:57,816
[SPEAKER_01]: New Bedford and Lexington, in their ordinances, a condo review board is established by this ordinance.

445
00:49:58,437 --> 00:50:01,800
[SPEAKER_01]: In Boston and in Marlborough, that isn't the case.

446
00:50:01,840 --> 00:50:08,085
[SPEAKER_01]: There are other existing city departments that are named and delegated as having different parts in the process.

447
00:50:08,145 --> 00:50:10,887
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe they do the conversion permits.

448
00:50:11,828 --> 00:50:13,109
[SPEAKER_01]: They do the conversion licenses.

449
00:50:13,189 --> 00:50:15,111
[SPEAKER_01]: If there's an eviction license, they might handle that.

450
00:50:16,686 --> 00:50:19,368
[SPEAKER_01]: and the responsibilities are kind of spread around.

451
00:50:20,109 --> 00:50:30,517
[SPEAKER_01]: In different cities, and this extends down to the next page, there are different levels of responsibilities afforded to these different departments, whether it's a review board or an existing city department.

452
00:50:31,958 --> 00:50:38,183
[SPEAKER_01]: For example, not surprisingly, Boston does a lot, because Boston is big and has a big budget.

453
00:50:38,683 --> 00:50:41,225
[SPEAKER_01]: The Office of Housing Stability is responsible for

454
00:50:42,923 --> 00:50:48,406
[SPEAKER_01]: establishing the process for conversion plans, approving or waiving, developing that entire system.

455
00:50:49,047 --> 00:50:54,790
[SPEAKER_01]: The Inspectional Services Department promulgates policies for the conversion permitting process.

456
00:50:55,290 --> 00:51:06,257
[SPEAKER_01]: The Office of Housing Stability is actually tasked with contacting current tenants and all recent tenants in a proposed condo conversion to determine if they're eligible for benefits under this ordinance.

457
00:51:06,277 --> 00:51:10,540
[SPEAKER_01]: So they'll actually do outreach to any tenant that conceivably might've been affected.

458
00:51:11,640 --> 00:51:16,944
[SPEAKER_01]: and then get back in touch with the landlord to make sure that conversion plan is set up for any tenants that are eligible.

459
00:51:17,564 --> 00:51:27,951
[SPEAKER_01]: And the Inspectional Services Department submits an annual report to the City Council on, you know, kind of in the line of the report that we heard about from Somerville, kind of an overview of how is this going?

460
00:51:28,011 --> 00:51:29,732
[SPEAKER_01]: What are the outcomes of this ordinance?

461
00:51:30,553 --> 00:51:31,794
[SPEAKER_01]: How is implementation going?

462
00:51:34,055 --> 00:51:35,056
[SPEAKER_01]: For another example,

463
00:51:37,031 --> 00:51:40,313
[SPEAKER_01]: in New Bedford, the Condo Review Board monitors conversions.

464
00:51:41,054 --> 00:51:44,676
[SPEAKER_01]: If somebody is claiming protected tenant status, it will verify that that's true.

465
00:51:45,477 --> 00:51:52,622
[SPEAKER_01]: It's also tasked with doing public awareness programming around the existence of this ordinance and maintaining data and statistics around this.

466
00:51:53,082 --> 00:51:59,726
[SPEAKER_01]: And I mentioned that I think this will be an interesting question for us to consider because

467
00:52:00,687 --> 00:52:09,955
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I think this has come up in some other recent ordinances that we've talked about that where maybe other examples existed where there was a specific board or commission set up to oversee it.

468
00:52:10,095 --> 00:52:18,202
[SPEAKER_01]: And we look at Wedford and we say, I don't know how much slack in the system we have for supporting a new department.

469
00:52:19,303 --> 00:52:26,489
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe the suggested tasks and responsibilities are outside the scope of what we would ask a volunteer commission to do.

470
00:52:28,768 --> 00:52:39,058
[SPEAKER_01]: in Somerville, I believe that their condo cooperative review board is at least largely volunteer or perhaps it's stipended, but these aren't members of city staff, they're residents.

471
00:52:39,938 --> 00:52:51,449
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think that we'll have to take a clear eyed look at what could we ask a review board to do that they could actually accomplish, especially since a lot of this is going to be fairly technical.

472
00:52:55,561 --> 00:52:58,487
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm scrolling down to page six.

473
00:53:02,133 --> 00:53:03,115
[SPEAKER_01]: Permitting process.

474
00:53:03,776 --> 00:53:05,419
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't think that's super interesting.

475
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:07,603
[SPEAKER_01]: The waivers and applicability.

476
00:53:09,618 --> 00:53:23,289
[SPEAKER_01]: I think is something that we might wanna look at, especially based on some of the comments that we just heard from city staff around the particularities of Medford in specific, who in our community is contemplating condo conversion?

477
00:53:23,509 --> 00:53:24,730
[SPEAKER_01]: How often is that a developer?

478
00:53:24,810 --> 00:53:26,471
[SPEAKER_01]: How often is that an owner occupier?

479
00:53:27,392 --> 00:53:31,715
[SPEAKER_01]: That's considering household finances in part of the equation.

480
00:53:31,735 --> 00:53:34,918
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think our decisions around

481
00:53:36,843 --> 00:53:46,725
[SPEAKER_01]: under what circumstances are requirements of this ordinance waived or parts of this ordinance are waived and what buildings are applicable or not, that could pertain to building size.

482
00:53:48,086 --> 00:53:55,447
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, we already talked about, you know, perhaps buildings, you know, units three and under, there's a question there as to how appropriate that is.

483
00:53:55,467 --> 00:54:01,349
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think another,

484
00:54:04,981 --> 00:54:14,988
[SPEAKER_01]: topic that the question of wave ability could lead us into is, you know, in what ways do we want this to be a lever for trying to create affordable housing or at least funding for affordable housing.

485
00:54:15,749 --> 00:54:23,214
[SPEAKER_01]: When for profit condo conversion is happening, maybe there's a lever that we can pull, such as the system that Marlboro has set up where

486
00:54:26,358 --> 00:54:40,305
[SPEAKER_01]: waiving parts of this ordinance can happen if certain conditions are met and those includes payments to the Affordable Housing Trust, increased payments to tenants if they've lived in the unit past certain thresholds or longevity bonuses to tenants.

487
00:54:41,986 --> 00:54:52,672
[SPEAKER_01]: If the condos meet an owner occupancy threshold, I think it's if more than 70% of the newly converted condos will be occupied by those owners, then they don't have to be subject to the requirements of this ordinance.

488
00:54:53,632 --> 00:55:18,200
[SPEAKER_01]: So those are ways to say, okay, maybe this ordinance creates some onerous requirements on people who want to convert rentals to condos, but if you can demonstrate that it's for the purposes of owner occupation, if you can commit to paying into affordable housing in the community, if you can compensate your tenants that are being displaced at a higher degree, then we can make this easier for you.

489
00:55:19,451 --> 00:55:38,990
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think that that's a lever that we might want to look at for for both of those reasons for the kind of general public interest in terms of affordable housing increasing affordable housing in the community being for the for the general public interest and also for private interest in terms of owner occupiers that might want to convert into a condo and for the private interest of tenants that are being displaced.

490
00:55:43,019 --> 00:55:44,240
[SPEAKER_04]: Great, thank you, Councillor Collins.

491
00:55:44,260 --> 00:55:46,621
[SPEAKER_04]: That was a lot of information.

492
00:55:46,641 --> 00:55:47,521
[SPEAKER_01]: Probably too much, sorry.

493
00:55:47,541 --> 00:55:49,202
[SPEAKER_04]: No, no, no.

494
00:55:49,662 --> 00:55:57,865
[SPEAKER_04]: It was just quite a bit of information, but I think we can see at least everything and the differences between what these five cities have done.

495
00:55:57,905 --> 00:56:02,948
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, we don't exactly know why, but I think we can start to at least infer why some did some things and some did others.

496
00:56:03,008 --> 00:56:10,611
[SPEAKER_04]: I thought that the 25%, only 25% of units in a structure can be converted a year seemed pretty targeted by Marlborough.

497
00:56:10,631 --> 00:56:12,352
[SPEAKER_04]: So for whatever reason, they passed that.

498
00:56:13,795 --> 00:56:15,037
[SPEAKER_04]: sure they had something in mind.

499
00:56:19,204 --> 00:56:25,716
[SPEAKER_04]: I heard kind of at least one or two places we want to go from here.

500
00:56:27,523 --> 00:56:36,330
[SPEAKER_04]: One was getting some more data and potentially some anecdotal contextual thoughts from our building department staff as offered by the commissioner.

501
00:56:36,350 --> 00:56:44,035
[SPEAKER_04]: Reaching out to the assessor's office to see what kind of data and information that they have as well that can inform this.

502
00:56:44,396 --> 00:56:47,998
[SPEAKER_04]: And Bill, did CitizenServe go into effect, what, 2020 or 2021?

503
00:56:48,459 --> 00:56:50,340
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I believe it was 2021.

504
00:56:51,041 --> 00:56:51,341
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

505
00:56:51,601 --> 00:56:56,825
[SPEAKER_04]: So maybe the assessor might be able to go back a little further, and we can kind of cross-check those two sets of data.

506
00:56:57,747 --> 00:57:06,669
[SPEAKER_04]: I think this other thought around what are the outcomes we're trying to achieve could potentially be a next step here, but that's just what I've heard.

507
00:57:07,370 --> 00:57:09,630
[SPEAKER_04]: Interested in what you're thinking and where you'd like to go from here.

508
00:57:10,130 --> 00:57:11,751
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I was thinking along the same lines.

509
00:57:11,811 --> 00:57:20,293
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that the process that I would like to see for this ordinance is a start with desired outcomes and kind of work backwards from there.

510
00:57:20,353 --> 00:57:24,394
[SPEAKER_01]: If we start with, here's what we're trying to protect against,

511
00:57:25,645 --> 00:57:54,116
[SPEAKER_01]: here's what we're trying to encourage, here are the incentives we'd potentially like to bake in if we can, here's who this is targeted at, here's what's not targeted at, and from there we can start, I think, or like one option is to look at some of these other municipalities and say, where is the example language that captures what we're trying to capture and what can we look at as a next jumping off point and say, okay, perhaps we're trying to include incentives for paying into an affordable housing fund or an affordable housing trust,

512
00:57:55,244 --> 00:57:56,564
[SPEAKER_01]: What are some ways to frame that?

513
00:57:56,864 --> 00:57:57,665
[SPEAKER_01]: How would that fit in?

514
00:57:58,105 --> 00:58:01,205
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe we're trying to make sure that owner occupiers are exempted.

515
00:58:01,225 --> 00:58:03,026
[SPEAKER_01]: How can we encapsulate that?

516
00:58:04,566 --> 00:58:14,348
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think from my perspective, brainstorming that list of key topics or key outcomes and going from there would be a great way to move this forward and start whittling.

517
00:58:17,749 --> 00:58:18,569
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

518
00:58:19,710 --> 00:58:20,330
[SPEAKER_04]: Lily, if I could.

519
00:58:22,069 --> 00:58:26,313
[SPEAKER_04]: go to your experience really quickly, or at least the research that you've done so far.

520
00:58:26,994 --> 00:58:34,200
[SPEAKER_04]: You mentioned that when you were doing your review, and if you wouldn't mind coming to the podium, just so that when you say something, people on Zoom can hear you.

521
00:58:36,002 --> 00:58:40,926
[SPEAKER_04]: You mentioned that it seemed like a lot of communities kind of looked at outcomes and then tailored ordinances around those outcomes.

522
00:58:40,987 --> 00:58:46,632
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you have an example of how those processes worked or what those kind of target outcomes were?

523
00:58:47,661 --> 00:58:59,890
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure, I think so I only looked at several I sort of looked at yesterday, but I think one of their biggest desired outcomes was greater protection for tenants and kind of ability to connect the tenants to new housing.

524
00:59:00,331 --> 00:59:09,638
[SPEAKER_02]: So one of the ways they specifically did this was to increase the payments really to kind of bring that in line to what was what is realistic to expect when looking for new housing.

525
00:59:10,088 --> 00:59:10,688
[SPEAKER_02]: in Somerville.

526
00:59:10,748 --> 00:59:17,092
[SPEAKER_02]: So really the goal there was to try as much as possible to keep people in their communities, give people time to look for new housing.

527
00:59:17,492 --> 00:59:29,919
[SPEAKER_02]: And I believe there, I don't remember the details, but there may have been an incentive for the property owners to help connect tenants with new housing and actually offer assistance in that way, rather than simply just offering the payments.

528
00:59:30,420 --> 00:59:36,703
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's kind of one example of like, they really had something very specific, giving people time to find a way to stay in their communities.

529
00:59:38,004 --> 00:59:38,244
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

530
00:59:38,705 --> 00:59:39,325
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much.

531
00:59:43,290 --> 00:59:44,010
[SPEAKER_04]: Any motions?

532
00:59:49,675 --> 00:59:50,555
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, I'm syncing.

533
00:59:51,276 --> 00:59:53,298
[SPEAKER_04]: I have two, but I can't make them.

534
00:59:54,598 --> 00:59:59,502
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, because I'm the only other one here.

535
01:00:00,283 --> 01:00:01,424
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, thanks.

536
01:00:06,067 --> 01:00:07,869
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I mean, my two thoughts for one, just request

537
01:00:08,958 --> 01:00:13,042
[SPEAKER_04]: data and any other information from the building department and the assessor's office.

538
01:00:14,183 --> 01:00:22,131
[SPEAKER_04]: And the other one being, I mean, I don't want to put work on any city departments around the brainstorming of outcomes.

539
01:00:24,994 --> 01:00:26,556
[SPEAKER_04]: But I was thinking something around that.

540
01:00:35,081 --> 01:00:51,386
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I was gonna say, I feel like that's a kind of easy discussion to have because I feel like there's probably a lot of outcomes that our city staff would like to wish for tenants and owner occupiers since we've heard so many, sorry, I keep smacking my mic, since we've heard a lot of them in this discussion already.

541
01:00:51,406 --> 01:01:04,270
[SPEAKER_01]: I think if there's maybe to not create undue work, I would love to circulate the documents and I can put this in the form of a motion from our meeting tonight,

542
01:01:05,054 --> 01:01:23,884
[SPEAKER_01]: among relevant city staff, just to ask maybe not necessarily for any type of in depth close read at this point because this is really just the beginning of the discussion, but asking for different departments feedback on outcomes to avoid outcomes to focus on, and maybe an example of that would be

543
01:01:24,288 --> 01:01:30,032
[SPEAKER_01]: Like Lily just said, the experience of the tenants, so an outcome would be making sure that tenants can remain in the community.

544
01:01:30,493 --> 01:01:44,623
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe another outcome is protecting owner occupiers or streamlining the process for owner occupiers, just to get that sort of top line bullet points, staff perspective on what we should be focusing on.

545
01:01:45,123 --> 01:01:50,447
[SPEAKER_04]: So maybe something to the effect of in, you know,

546
01:01:52,695 --> 01:02:07,639
[SPEAKER_04]: share documents with city departments and invite any department and members of the subcommittee to submit goals that they think this ordinance could achieve and potential negative consequences that we should avoid.

547
01:02:07,659 --> 01:02:17,222
[SPEAKER_04]: So sure, I just want to make sure the clerk has it.

548
01:02:18,542 --> 01:02:21,923
[SPEAKER_02]: I just wanted to add that I'd be happy to reach out to other communities.

549
01:02:22,375 --> 01:02:30,598
[SPEAKER_02]: and get both updated reports if they have formal reports, and also kind of ask them if they have anything to report about how their ordinances are going.

550
01:02:30,658 --> 01:02:31,959
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there anything they would change?

551
01:02:31,979 --> 01:02:33,620
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'm happy to do that.

552
01:02:33,660 --> 01:02:39,702
[SPEAKER_02]: And also to look at our own housing production plan and comprehensive plan with an eye to sort of seeing where this might fit in.

553
01:02:39,722 --> 01:02:41,083
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, great.

554
01:02:43,624 --> 01:02:49,646
[SPEAKER_06]: I have council calls for the circulatory documents and subcommittee members that don't have city employees for feedback and comments.

555
01:02:49,946 --> 01:02:51,367
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I'd say for feedback on

556
01:02:52,384 --> 01:02:52,584
[SPEAKER_04]: Um.

557
01:02:53,885 --> 01:02:56,686
[SPEAKER_04]: Goals the potential ordinance could help achieve.

558
01:03:00,727 --> 01:03:02,628
[SPEAKER_04]: And potential negative consequences.

559
01:03:03,128 --> 01:03:04,548
[SPEAKER_04]: Any ordinance should avoid.

560
01:03:04,568 --> 01:03:16,953
[SPEAKER_04]: And then could we add the building department to the first motion?

561
01:03:18,273 --> 01:03:19,574
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry, not the building, but the planning department.

562
01:03:19,594 --> 01:03:19,974
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry.

563
01:03:33,783 --> 01:03:34,603
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

564
01:03:38,985 --> 01:03:43,607
[SPEAKER_05]: The vice president request data and other information from the building department, PDS and the assessor's office.

565
01:03:44,327 --> 01:03:44,907
[SPEAKER_04]: Yep, great.

566
01:03:44,927 --> 01:03:46,027
[SPEAKER_05]: Second from Councilor Collins.

567
01:03:46,067 --> 01:03:49,489
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm giving you a second on Councilor Collins' motion.

568
01:03:49,789 --> 01:03:50,469
[SPEAKER_04]: The only option.

569
01:03:51,069 --> 01:03:53,070
[SPEAKER_04]: Correct.

570
01:03:53,190 --> 01:04:00,672
[SPEAKER_04]: So on those two motions, or on the motion of, on my motion seconded by Councilor Collins, all those in favor?

571
01:04:01,032 --> 01:04:01,112
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

572
01:04:01,312 --> 01:04:01,433
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

573
01:04:02,053 --> 01:04:02,513
[SPEAKER_04]: Opposed?

574
01:04:03,588 --> 01:04:04,909
[SPEAKER_04]: The motion passes.

575
01:04:06,049 --> 01:04:08,711
[SPEAKER_04]: On the motion of Councilor Collins, seconded by me.

576
01:04:08,811 --> 01:04:09,491
[SPEAKER_04]: All those in favor?

577
01:04:09,831 --> 01:04:09,931
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

578
01:04:10,432 --> 01:04:10,552
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

579
01:04:11,312 --> 01:04:12,032
[SPEAKER_04]: Opposed?

580
01:04:12,312 --> 01:04:12,553
[SPEAKER_04]: No.

581
01:04:12,813 --> 01:04:13,633
[SPEAKER_04]: Motion passes.

582
01:04:14,714 --> 01:04:15,814
[SPEAKER_04]: So those two motions have passed.

583
01:04:15,834 --> 01:04:20,317
[SPEAKER_04]: Is there anything anyone else would want to say at this time before we close out?

584
01:04:22,658 --> 01:04:26,700
[SPEAKER_04]: Seeing none in the room, anyone on Zoom, if you would like to speak, please raise your hand.

585
01:04:31,880 --> 01:04:33,642
[SPEAKER_04]: Seeing none, are there any motions on the floor?

586
01:04:33,662 --> 01:04:35,563
[SPEAKER_01]: Motion to adjourn.

587
